Plants undergo both sexual and asexual reproduction

## Three plant lifecycle types
- Annuals
	- Live and reproduce within 12 months
	- IE Marigolds
- Biennials
	- Produce foliage one year, inflorescences the second year
- Perennials
	- Plants that live and flower for more than 2 years
	- Significant research into making non-perennial plants 
		- Corn is not perennial
			- But [[Teosinte\|Teosinte]] is!
			- So we might be able to splice some of those genes into corn

## Asexual reproduction
- Cloning, no mixing of genetics
	- Bad long-term strategy because there's no [[Unsorted/Biodiversity\|Biodiversity]]
	- In short term, it can help propagate quickly
- Two types
	- Vegetative: Utilize almost any fragment or part of a plant body
		- Without [[Unsorted/Humans\|human]] intervention
			- Bulbs, tuvers, rhizomes, runners (stolons)
			- Often happens entirely underground
			- Bulbs
				- Underground storage organ, formed from ~~stem/leaves~~ buds
				- Bottom of bulb has thick disk called the basal plate
					- Compressed stem
					- Roots grow from this
				- Body is made of layers of fleshy scales, modified leaves
				- The center has a bub
			- Corms
				- aka bulbotuber
				- Swollen underground plant stem
			- Tubers
				- IE potato, cassava, sweet potato
				- Meant to help plants survive winter
				- Fleshy storage organ formed from a stem or root
				- Potato tubers form at the end of the underground stem
					- Can produce new shoots from buds on its surface
				- Some plants only use them for storage, not reproduction
			- Rhizomes
				- Stems that grow underground
				- Grows horizontally
				- Because it's a stem, it has nodes, and can make new stems that go up aboveground
					- Like cypress trees
				- Used to store energy
				- Common in weedy plants
			- Stolons (Runners)
				- Stems that grow on the surface then root downwards
		- With [[Unsorted/Humans\|human]] intervention
			- Cuttings, grafting, tissue culture, layering
			- Layering
				- When a portion of a stem grows roots then detaches as an indeendent plant
			- Cuttings
				- Works because of meristomatic tissue
					- Allows root cells to emerge when in the right environment
			- Tissue culture
				- Cloning via small slivers of meristomatic tissue
	- Systems that depend upon specialized structures that have evolved as reproductive agents

## Sexual reproduction
- 2 parents (male and female)
- Slow process
- Gamete formation and fertilization
- Mixes genes, creating genetic and physiological diversity
	- How new varieties of plants are created
	- Verrryyy slow process, respectable work
		- Often protected by patents

### Flower types
- Perfect flowers, have male + female parts
	- Likely self-fertile, but there's mechanisms to prevent it
- Imperfect male flowers (staminate)
	- Androecium
	- Stamen, filament, anther, pollen
	- Produces pollen but will never produce fruit
	- ![c81a56dd04104df7d803a5a7ea066799-2030200682.jpg](data:image/png;base64,)
- Imperfect female (pistillate)
	- Gynoecium
		- Single carpel or multiple fused ones
		- Pistil
			- Contains obule, ovaries, style, stigma
	- Produce fruit if ovaries are pollinated
	- When unfertilized
		- Doesn't grow much, but can resemble fertilized fruits
		- Will wilt and fall off

- Mulberries are genderfluid
	- Frequently change sexes
	- Individuals can be dioecious (Only one sex)
